  "prompt": "What is a principal root? How is it used in Mathematics?",
  "response": "A principal root is a specific concept in mathematics, primarily used in algebra and complex number theory. Let me explain its meaning and usage:\n\n1. Definition:\n- The principal root is the root of a number with the smallest non-negative angle in the complex plane\n- It is typically the root with the smallest positive argument (angle)\n\n2. Real Numbers:\n- For positive real numbers, the principal root is the positive square root\n- Example: The principal root of 16 is +4, not -4\n\n3. Complex Numbers:\n- For complex numbers, the principal root has a specific range of argument\n- Usually between -\u03c0 and \u03c0 (or 0 and 2\u03c0, depending on the convention)\n\n4. Uses:\n- Simplifying complex number calculations\n- Defining multi-valued functions like square roots\n- Resolving ambiguity in root calculations\n- Used in trigonometry and advanced algebra\n\n5. Example:\n- The principal square root of -1 is i\n- The principal cube root of 8 is 2\n\n6. Notation:\n- Often denoted with a special symbol or superscript\n- Example: \u221a or \u221b for principal roots\n\nThe principal root helps standardize root calculations in mathematics.",
